SIMPLE: glory
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glory
<hw>Glo"ry</hw> <pr>(gl⟦omac⟧"r⟦ycr⟧; 111)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>glorie</ets>, OF. <ets>glorie</ets>, <ets>gloire</ets>, F.
<ets>gloire</ets>, fr. L. <ets>gloria</ets>; prob. akin to Gr.
<grk>kle`os</grk>, Skr. <ets>⟦cced⟧ravas</ets> glory, praise,
<ets>⟦cced⟧ru</ets> to hear. See <er>Loud</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Praise, honor, admiration, or distinction, accorded by common
consent to a person or thing; high reputation; honorable fame;
renown.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Glory</qex> to God in the highest.</q> <rj><qau>Luke ii.
14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spread his <qex>glory</qex> through all countries wide.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That quality in a person or thing which secures
general praise or honor; that which brings or gives renown; an object of
pride or boast; the occasion of praise; excellency; brilliancy;
splendor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Think it no <qex>glory</qex> to swell in tyranny.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jewels lose their <qex>glory</qex> if neglected.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your sex's <qex>glory</qex> 't is to shine unknown.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Pride; boastfulness; arrogance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>glory</qex> of thy fortunes.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The presence of the Divine Being; the manifestations
of the divine nature and favor to the blessed in heaven; celestial
honor; heaven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt guide me with thy counsel, and afterward receive me to
<qex>glory</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxxiii. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An emanation of light supposed to proceed from
beings of peculiar sanctity. It is represented in art by rays of gold,
or the like, proceeding from the head or body, or by a disk, or a mere
line.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This is the general term; when confined to the head it
is properly called <xex>nimbus</xex>; when encircling the whole body,
<xex>aureola</xex> or <xex>aureole</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Glory hole</b></col>, <cd>an opening in the wall of a
glass furnace, exposing the brilliant white light of the interior.</cd>
<au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Glory pea</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>,
<cd>the name of two leguminous plants (<spn>Clianthus Dampieri</spn> and
<spn>C. puniceus</spn>) of Australia and New Zeland. They have showy
scarlet or crimson flowers.</cd> -- <col><b>Glory tree</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a name given to several species of the
verbenaceous genus <gen>Clerodendron</gen>, showy flowering shrubs of
tropical regions.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glory</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Glory
<hw>Glo"ry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Gloried</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Glorying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>glorien</ets>, OF.
<ets>glorier</ets>, fr. L. <ets>gloriari</ets>, fr. <ets>gloria</ets>
glory. See <er>Glory</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To exult with joy; to rejoice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Glory</qex> ye in his holy name.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
cv.<?/</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To boast; to be proud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God forbid that I should <qex>glory</qex>, save in the cross of
our Lord Jesus Christ.</q> <rj><qau>Gal. vi. 14</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No one . . . should <qex>glory</qex> in his prosperity.</q>
<rj><qau>Richardson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glose</ent>⟦br⟧
